1. Chosen Development Model
Model: Agile
Justification: We chose the agile model because it is flexible and easy to adapt. Since the project requirements can change during development, Agile allows us to make updates without affecting the whole system.

2. User Requirements
a. Stakeholders (WHO is involved)
• Teachers
Use the system to record attendance, enter grades, and communicate with students. They want to reduce paperwork and save time.
• Students
Access their grades, schedules, and announcements. They want quick and easy access to their school information.
• IT staff
Oversee the system’s operation, maintain servers and databases, and ensure that the software works smoothly. They are interested in system stability, backups, and troubleshooting.
b. User Stories (WHAT they need and WHY)
As a teacher, I want to mark attendance online so that I don’t need to use paper registers.
As a teacher, I want to enter student grades so that students can see their results easily.
As a student, I want to check my grades online so that I can track my performance.
As a student, I want to see my class schedule so that I know when my lessons are.
As an IT staff member, I want to manage user accounts so that teachers and students can log in and use the system safely.
As an IT staff member, I want to perform regular backups so that all data (grades, attendance, documents) is safe in case of system failure.
As an IT staff member, I want to monitor system performance so that any issues are detected and fixed quickly.
As an IT staff member, I want to update the system software so that new features or security updates can be applied without downtime.
As an IT staff member, I want to troubleshoot technical issues so that teachers and students can continue using the system without interruptions.
As an IT staff member, I want to control access permissions so that only authorized users can perform sensitive actions like entering grades or approving documents.

